english:
  title: Record of the Heart-Washing Pavilion
  author: Lee Seung-so
  language: eng
  text: |-
    South of the capital, only a few miles beyond the city walls, a great river flows from the east, embracing the mountainside as it courses westward. At its crossing—the Han River Ford—stands the济川Pavilion. A hundred paces beyond it rises the Heart-Washing Pavilion, each commanding its share of the river and mountains' beauty. Yet in the seclusion of its wooded valleys and the breadth of its vistas, the latter surpasses the former. This pavilion is the country retreat of the Lord of Silver Valley.

    The Lord once wrote to me saying: "I have served under the favor of King Sejong for more than a decade, yet now weakened by age and illness, I grow weary of official life. Long have I dreamed of withdrawing to some quiet, remote shore to spend my remaining years in peace. At last my wish is granted. I have built my foundation here by the river and constructed a small pavilion as a place of repose, which I have named 'Heart-Washing.' I pray you expound its meaning for me."

    Alas! Though I have long sought with my humble learning to wash my own heart, I have scarcely grasped even its shadow. How dare I presume to explain it? I can only speak of what seems near to truth.

    Man alone among all creatures possesses a spirit that stands equal with Heaven and Earth to form the Three Powers. This spirit has a luminous, undeluded essence, a radiant use unburdened by attachment—it should require no external washing. Yet bound by bodily form and obscured by material desires, the clear grows daily dim, the spiritual grows daily rigid, until we sink into ignorance and unworthiness. Thus did the ancients labor at the work of washing.

    Now, in his leisure from public duty, the Lord walks these pavilion heights in simple cap and staff, where river and mountain smile bright, where wind and scene glow pure, where the dust of the world cannot reach. Here, what pleases the eye and gladdens the heart may indeed wash away dullness and care. Yet this alone suffices not.

    For the heart's function moves only between attraction and aversion, and when either inclines, the heart becomes defiled. Those who delight in landscape and admire mist, cloud, flower, and bird—though their pleasures differ in refinement from those who toil for daily bread—share equally this dependence on external things. Indeed, seated restlessly in the pavilion, glancing left and right, forever responding to impressions, the mind dances with every passing sensation, becoming entangled in what it perceives, warring with itself each day.

    Only when self and world cease to oppose, when preference and aversion lose their partiality, when one responds to things yet remains untouched by them—only then do marketplace and mountain alike become places of heart-washing, and the clear, empty, luminous nature reveals itself spontaneously.

    The Book of Changes praises the divining stalk thus: "The sage washes his heart thereby and retires into secrecy." The stalk reveals fortune and misfortune, guides approach and avoidance, accomplishes all under Heaven—through no thought, no calculation, only impartial response. So too the sage's heart: free from even a thread of selfish attachment, prescient as the divine, therefore it is said "the sage washes his heart thereby."

    From this we understand: only when one acts without self-seeking, when things cannot soil the heart, can one truly be said to have washed it. Now the Lord, employing the sage's method to wash his heart while dwelling in this clear, untainted realm, finds inner and outer nourishing each other—surely he shall walk the path of the sages.

    But should he merely linger in the pavilion gazing at the broad river and suppose that ten thousand measures of clear water can wash the heart—of this I know nothing.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: King Sejong (世祖 Sejong) refers to the fourth king of the Joseon dynasty, known for his scholarly patronage.
  - key: ''
    value: The "Book of Changes" reference is to the I Ching (易經), one of the foundational texts of East Asian philosophy, particularly its commentary known as the Ten Wings (繫辭).
  - key: ''
    value: The philosophical concept of "washing the heart" (洗心) relates to Neo-Confucian self-cultivation, emphasizing the purification of the mind from material desires and selfish attachments to achieve spiritual clarity.
